The Trump administration's claim that the Federal Reserve lacks the funds to finance the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau isn't merely wrong. It is wrong in a way that strongly suggests the people making it know better.

The argument runs as follows: Dodd-Frank funds the CFPB through the Fed's "combined earnings." Because the Fed has reported negative net income since 2022, there are no earnings to draw from‚Äîand therefore no money for the CFPB. End of story.

On the surface, this sounds plausible. The Fed has accumulated roughly $242 billion in accounting losses as of September 2025. Those losses stem from a mismatch between the low-yield bonds the Fed bought during the COVID era and the higher interest it now pays on bank reserves. On paper, its liabilities exceed what would normally be labeled equity.

But that framing collapses under minimal scrutiny. The Federal Reserve is not a business. It is the central bank of the United States. It creates money. It cannot "run out" of funds the way a private institution can. The Fed itself has been explicit: negative net income and the resulting "deferred asset" do not impair its ability to meet its obligations or conduct monetary policy.

More damning, the Fed's losses are not some external calamity. They are the direct result of discretionary policy choices.

For nearly a century‚Äîfrom 1913 until 2008‚Äîthe Federal Reserve paid no interest on bank reserves. None. It lacked the legal authority to do so until Congress granted it in 2006, and it didn't begin paying until the 2008 financial crisis, when the policy was adopted as an emergency measure to stabilize banks by putting a floor under their earnings.

What began as a temporary rescue became permanent subsidy. Today, the Fed pays tens of billions of dollars annually in interest on reserves to banks‚Äîincluding foreign banks operating in the United States. If the Fed stopped these payments, its income would turn positive almost immediately. It continues to pay because it prefers this method of implementing monetary policy, not because it is legally compelled to do so.

So the administration's position reduces to this: the Fed is "out of money" because it is voluntarily transferring tens of billions to banks, and therefore cannot fund an agency designed to protect consumers from those same banks.

The Fed accounts for its temporary losses through a "deferred asset"‚Äîa bookkeeping mechanism that records negative earnings to be offset by future profits. This is an accounting convention, not a liquidity crisis. Throughout this period, the Fed has met every obligation without interruption. It has never suggested it lacked the capacity to transfer funds.

That makes the timing revealing. For over a decade, across multiple interest-rate regimes, the CFPB received its quarterly funding from the Fed without controversy. The statute did not change. What changed was the arrival of an administration determined to eliminate the agency.

Only then did the Justice Department's Office of Legal Counsel produce a novel interpretation of "combined earnings," conveniently timed as a workaround for court orders blocking mass layoffs at the CFPB. As Judge Amy Berman Jackson noted, this interpretation was a "sharp departure" from longstanding practice and appeared to be "an unsupported and transparent attempt to starve the CFPB of funding."

Russell Vought‚Äîsimultaneously OMB Director and acting CFPB head‚Äîwas more candid still. In October, he said he hoped to "close down" the agency within months. When someone announces intent to kill an institution and then unveils a bespoke legal theory explaining why it must die, skepticism is not cynicism. It is common sense.

This argument did not emerge organically from statutory ambiguity. It was incubated in conservative legal circles as a weapon to defund the CFPB, waiting for an administration willing to deploy it. It treats the nation's central bank as if it were a small credit union that overdrew its checking account. The people advancing it have access to economists, lawyers, and the Fed's own published statements explaining why the premise is false.

They advanced it anyway‚Äîwhile the Fed continues to funnel billions to banks. That alone tells you whether they believe the argument, and whose interests they are actually serving.
